nobismetipsis] Here the critics disagree. In the oration Quum Senatui, c. l, he has the same expression, and he uses it in the common sense. You have restored to me my brother, and every thing, finally you have restored me to myself; which means you have restored me to my former con- dition3 you have made me again what I was. Here he says ⁴ you have restored me not to a number of kinsmen, but to myself,’ meaning ‘not at the entreaty or for the sake of numerous kinsfolk, but for my own

sake.’ Markland points out this unusual use of the words; and Gesner defends it. Wolf as usual falls upon Gesner, affirms that Markland is right, and ends with 3 very instructive remark z ‘⁴ Ac ne quis putet Ciceronem, utpote Romanum, aliquid audere potuisse in patria lingua: potuit utique; sed multa sunt in quibus eum noluisse, quod posset, appareat. Ita potuit etiam inepte scribere: sed id noluit facere; atque adeo diu noluit, ut tandem ne posset qui- dem. Hoc valet de rebus multis.''

Klotz defends the text and the meaning, which is, he says, “ you have restored me not out of regar-d to the number of my kinsfolk, as this in other like cases was done, but simply out of regard to myself.”
